ğŸ”¹ What is venv (Virtual Environment)?

venv is an isolated Python environment created per project.

It keeps:

Python packages

Package versions

Dependencies

separate from system Python.

ğŸ‘‰ Think of venv like a lightweight Docker container for Python.

ğŸ”¹ Why venv is Required (Very Important)
1ï¸âƒ£ Avoid Dependency Conflicts

Different projects need different versions.

Example:

Project A â†’ numpy 1.26

Project B â†’ numpy 1.21

Without venv â†’ conflict
With venv â†’ no issue

2ï¸âƒ£ Protect System Python (Ubuntu Rule)

Ubuntu uses Python for OS tools.

Installing packages globally can:

Break OS commands

Break apt

Cause security issues

venv keeps OS Python safe.

3ï¸âƒ£ Mandatory for DevOps / MLOps

Used in:

CI/CD pipelines

Docker images

ML training jobs

Kubernetes workloads

No company runs ML without virtual environments.

4ï¸âƒ£ Reproducible Builds

Same code + same venv = same result
Critical for AI models & production systems.

ğŸ”¹ When to Use venv

âœ” Every Python project
âœ” Every ML / AI project
âœ” Every CI/CD job
âœ” Every Docker build

Rule: One project = one venv

ğŸ”¹ Steps to Install & Configure venv (Ubuntu / WSL)
Step 1ï¸âƒ£ Install Required Packages (One-Time)
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y python3 python3-venv python3-pip
Step 2ï¸âƒ£ Go to Project Directory
cd ~/workspace/local-repo/devops-lab/python
Step 3ï¸âƒ£ Create Virtual Environment
python3 -m venv venv

Creates a folder:

python/
â””â”€â”€ venv/
Step 4ï¸âƒ£ Activate Virtual Environment
